## What I changed

The fresh-eyes review was right about the standout gap: three defining career pieces were missing. I verified the facts, then closed them.

- **Dickinson (the big one)** — Added a paragraph to the worth-wound section. She spent three seasons playing Emily Dickinson, a poet who made her life's work for no audience and died unrecognized, while being a Type 3 who can't bank her own applause. The review called this "either the strongest evidence or the sharpest counter-case." I wrote it as both: *"Maybe the part drew her because it was the one thing she finds impossible to imagine... Maybe she was practicing. For a Three, those are not far apart."*
- **Pitch Perfect + the music** — Named *Pitch Perfect 2* as the acting→music on-ramp and the singles "Love Myself" / "Starving" / "Most Girls." I leaned only "Love Myself" and "Most Girls" on the worth-wound point, since research showed "Starving" is actually a romance song — the review had lumped all three together.
- **Spider-Gwen** — Folded in as a control-the-channel illustration: voice work where she gives up her face and keeps only the performance no editor can undercut.
- **Sinners** — Expanded with the actual role. She plays Mary, a mixed-race woman passing as white, and Coogler coached her through being read as neither fully Black nor white — which maps directly onto her own heritage. Makes the interior turn hit harder.
- **Trim** — Cut the key-stat "14" box; that fact already lands three times in prose.

## What I deliberately kept

The Jo-Ann skirt spine, "it landed as a bill," and the humblebrag empathy turn — all untouched, as the review advised. "100 times as hard" stays bookended only.

## Still open

Spider-Gwen and the song-irony beat both live in the "vanishing" section, which is now the densest part of the piece. If an editor pass finds it crowded, the Spider-Gwen sentence is the cleanest thing to cut. Otherwise the draft is in good shape — the thesis is now backed by concrete evidence instead of asserted.
